  <p>Lobster landings in Maine have increased steadily in the last six decades, in 2018 a record-breaking 250 millions of pounds of lobster was harvested. However, many lobstermen remember the years when the catch, and therefore the salary was under. Still, they were hopeful that the lobster population, directly dependent on climate, would recover. But today, despite the landings at an all time high, a different force is threatening the livelihood of Maine fisheries. 
</p>
  <p>In July 2018, China, the largest market outside of North American for the Maine lobster, imposed 25 percent punitive tariffs on goods coming form the United States. The Maine lobster, an industry worth 1.4 billion dollars, is among the goods that is being hit with retaliatory tariffs.
